        "assistant": "**Cogalent pruning** differs from **structured pruning** in the basis for removal:\n\n- **Structured pruning** removes predefined structural units based on the model’s geometry or architecture, such as entire channels, filters, neurons, heads, layers, or blocks. The pruning unit is determined by the structure.\n\n- **Cogalent pruning** removes elements based on **joint redundancy across paired elements**. It identifies pairs that are co-redundant, keeps one member of the pair, and drops the other. The pruning decision is driven by redundancy between elements, not by the architectural unit they belong to.\n\nIn short:\n\n> **Structured pruning is geometry-driven; cogalent pruning is paired-redundancy-driven.**\n\nSo structured pruning might remove an entire channel because channels are the chosen structural unit, while cogalent pruning would remove one element from a redundant pair even if that pair does not correspond to a standard structural block.",
